# Java Spring Boot Coding Standards

**Target: Java 21.** Prefer Java 21 language and API features in all new code.

## Java 21 Conventions

- **Records** for DTOs, request/response types, and immutable value objects: `record ItemResponse(Long id, String name) {}`.
- **Pattern matching**: use `instanceof` with binding (`if (x instanceof Point p) { ... }`) and switch with patterns or guards when it simplifies control flow.
- **Unnamed variables**: use `_` for unused bindings (e.g. `catch (Exception _)`, lambda params, or pattern variables you don’t need).
- **`var`**: use where the type is obvious from the right-hand side and readability improves; avoid when the type is non-obvious or helps document the code.
- **`Optional`**: prefer `optional.orElseThrow()` (no-arg) when you expect a value and want to throw `NoSuchElementException`, or throw a custom exception in a method reference.
- **Sequenced collections** (Java 21): prefer `list.getFirst()` / `getLast()` and `addFirst()` / `addLast()` on `List` instead of index hacks.
- **Text blocks**: use `"""..."""` for multi-line string literals (SQL, JSON snippets, messages).
- **Virtual threads**: consider `ExecutorService` with virtual threads for I/O-bound concurrency where it fits (e.g. parallel calls); Spring Boot 3.2+ supports virtual-thread-based web servers when configured.

## Naming & Structure

- **Packages**: Lowercase, reverse domain (e.g. `com.bridge.code_challenge`). Group by feature or layer: `controller`, `service`, `repository`, `model`, `dto`, `config`, `exception`.
- **Classes**: PascalCase. Controllers: `*Controller`; services: `*Service`; repositories: `*Repository`; DTOs: `*Request`, `*Response`, `*Dto`; entities: noun singular.
- **Methods/variables**: camelCase. REST handlers: verb or `get*`, `create*`, `update*`, `delete*`.

## Spring Boot Conventions

- Prefer constructor injection for dependencies (enables `final` and immutability).
- Use `@RestController` + `@RequestMapping` at class level; `@GetMapping`, `@PostMapping`, etc. on methods.
- Return `ResponseEntity<T>` (or a wrapper) for REST APIs so status and headers are explicit.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/items")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ItemController {
    private final ItemService itemService;

    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<ItemResponse> getById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(itemService.findById(id));
    }
}
```

## Error Handling

- Do not swallow exceptions. Use `@ControllerAdvice` (or `@RestControllerAdvice`) with `@ExceptionHandler` for consistent API error responses.
- Log with context (e.g. identifier, operation) before rethrowing or mapping to a response.

```java
// ❌ BAD
try {
    return service.find(id);
} catch (Exception e) {}

// ✅ GOOD
@ExceptionHandler(ResourceNotFoundException.class)
public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleNotFound(ResourceNotFoundException ex) {
    log.warn("Resource not found: {}", ex.getMessage());
    return ResponseEntity.status(NOT_FOUND).body(new ErrorResponse(ex.getMessage()));
}
```

## General Java

- Prefer `final` for local variables and fields when they are not reassigned.
- Use meaningful names; avoid single-letter names except for loop indices or lambdas (e.g. `e` for exception). Use `_` for intentionally unused variables (Java 21).
- Keep methods short; extract private methods or separate services when logic grows.

```java
// ✅ Java 21: records for DTOs; pattern matching; orElseThrow()
public record ItemResponse(Long id, String name) {}

Item item = itemRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow(ResourceNotFoundException::new);
if (item instanceof ItemWithDiscount d) { return d.discountedPrice(); }
```
